		<div class="post" id="post-1702715">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1702715)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1702715">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/spikebrennan" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(908688); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=908688&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225562" alt="spikebrennan" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=908688)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/spikebrennan" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(908688); return false;" >spikebrennan</a></span> <span class="odate time_1359990279 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">04 Feb 2013 15:04</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1702715">
									

<p>Brilliantly written. Well done, Photosynthetic. All my +1.</p>
<p>The author and I carried on a little bit of correspondence before she drafted this. I'll just post some of my half of the exchange:<br />
&#8212;-<br />
&#8230; When I wrote SCP-1322, I intentionally omitted most of the details about the Hartle culture. Part of this was in order to make it a short story rather than a longer world-building exercise, but another part of it was in order to implicitly get across the fact that, fundamentally, the Foundation really isn't all that interested in the Hartle culture. They're more interested in the anomaly itself— in whether it constitutes a threat that needs to be secured and contained.</p>
<p>So you could pretty much make up whatever you wanted about the Hartle culture. My preference, however, is that if you do so, don't make broad-brush statements (like &quot;the reason they're not interested in hearing about our medicine or religion is that they're deeply devoted to their own religion, which has Christian Science-like notions about healing&quot;). Even though your story would not really be canonical, plenty of people are going to assume that your Hartle is the same as the one in my head&#8230;</p>
<p>&#8212;-</p>
<p>One more thing I'll say— I think it's important to stress that the SCP-1322-1 civilization is, basically, regular people. Like us. They're not incomprehensibly foreign. This is part of what makes the tragedy of my original piece work. A piece about sterilizing a planet inhabited by inscrutable hive-mind lobster people or whatever would be a shame, but not necessarily a tragedy which is why I didn't write it that way. Instead, these folks have families. They write poetry. They go on vacation and sit on the beach and watch the sun set.</p>
<p>The other half of the tragedy is that this whole society is slowly but inexorably dying, but the Foundation doesn't give a fuck. The bastards.</p>
<p>&#8212;-</p>
<p>(TL;DR: The SCP-1322 in this piece is a bit different than the one in my head-canon, but I love this piece. It makes the original 1322 even more tragic, because in my head-canon the Foundation's relationship with the other side was much, much more cold and detached. In my imagination, the Hartle folks are in a sense much more &quot;human&quot; than the Foundation people on &quot;our&quot; side.)</p>

							</div>

								
					
